definition.value: Any of a number of aggregations of neurons, glial cells and their processes, and surrounded by a glial cell and connective tissue sheath (plural: ganglia).

value.value: Multi-cell component structure of the central nervous system consisting largely of neuron projections (tracts and synaptic neuropil domains) and associated glial cells. This corresponds to the part of the CNS that is enclosed by the cortex.
A segmental subdivision of the nervous system.
Region of the peripheral nervous system where a motor neuron axon makes synaptic contacts on a target muscle.
A supporting cell of the nervous system.
Progenitor cell that gives rise only to glial cells and not neurons (Hartenstein, 2011).

Precursor of the central nervous system that derives from the neurogenic region of the ectoderm or the mesectoderm (Doe, 1992; Schmid et al., 1999; Crews, 2019). It produces neurons and/or glia (Doe, 1992; Beckervordersandforth et al., 2008). Neuroblasts may also divide during adult life to regenerate the adult brain (Fernandez-Hernandez et al., 2013).

definition.value: Adult neurogenesis demonstrated in the adult optic lobe in response to injury (Fernandez-Hernandez et al., 2013).

value.value: Precursor cell that gives rise to both neurons and glia (Hartenstein, 2011).
A cell of a proneural cluster of the neurectoderm, that will become either a neuroblast or an epidermoblast (Campos-Ortega, 1995).
Daughter cell formed through asymmetric division of a neuroblast, typically generating two postmitotic neurons.
Any glial cell that is part of (either layer of) the perineurium, which surrounds the entire nervous system (Kremer et al., 2017).

Glial cell that forms part of the perineurial sheath forming the outer layer of the nervous system. These cells divide extensively to increase in number as the nervous system expands during development (Kremer et al., 2017).
Multicellular anatomical structure with largely bona fide boundary that transduces some sensory stimulus to the nervous system.
Any sense organ (FBbt:00005155) that is capable of some detection of mechanical stimulus involved in sensory perception (GO:0050974).
Any sense organ (FBbt:00005155) that is capable of some detection of chemical stimulus involved in sensory perception (GO:0050907).
Any sense organ (FBbt:00005155) that is capable of some detection of chemical stimulus involved in sensory perception of smell (GO:0050911).
Any sense organ (FBbt:00005155) that is capable of some detection of temperature stimulus involved in sensory perception (GO:0050961).
Any sense organ (FBbt:00005155) that is capable of some detection of humidity stimulus involved in sensory perception (GO:0098512).
A light sensitive sense organ.
Any somatic cell (FBbt:00100318) that overlaps some sense organ (FBbt:00005155).
Precursor cell that gives rise to at least one cell of an external sensory organ.

label.value: external sensory organ precursor cell I

value.value: First-order precursor cell: mother of all the clonally related cells of an external sensory organ.

label.value: external sensory organ precursor cell IIa

value.value: Second-order precursor cell that develops from an external sensory organ precursor cell I. In the microchaete lineage, it divides to give rise to the tormogen cell and the trichogen cell of an external sensory organ (Gho et al., 1999; Hartenstein and Posakony, 1989). In the development of antennal olfactory sensilla, it produces two daughters, pOa and pOb, which each divide asymmetrically to produce the four types of support cell per sensillum (Endo et al., 2012; Chai et al., 2019).

label.value: external sensory organ precursor cell IIb

value.value: Second-order precursor cell that develops from an external sensory organ precursor cell I. In the microchaete lineage, it divides to give rise to the thecogen cell and the neuron of an external sensory organ (Gho et al., 1999; Hartenstein and Posakony, 1989). In the development of antennal olfactory sensilla, it produces two daughters, pNa and pNb, which each divide asymmetrically to produce up to four types of olfactory neuron per sensillum (Endo et al., 2012; Chai et al., 2019).
Sensory organ that has external structures that detect mechanical or chemical stimuli.
The eo accessory cell that makes the innervated cuticular sensory structure of an eo-type sensillum.
A cuticle-like matrix secreted by the thecogen cell around the tip of the eo dendrite(s).

definition.value: Formerly, erroneously called 'thecogen dendritic cap cell'.

value.value: The eo accessory cell that makes the socket that supports the innervated cuticular sensory structure of an eo-type sensillum.
The eo accessory cell that makes the thecogen dendritic cap - a cuticle-like matrix around the tip of the eo-dendrite and which encloses the soma of the eo-neuron.
Sensory neuron that is part of an eo-sensillum and whose dendrite innervates the cuticular external sensory structure of that sensillum.
Dendrite of an eo neuron, that innervates the cuticular external sensory structure of that sensillum.

The external sensory structure that is part of a trichogen cell. It can have a variety of shapes, including bristles with pointed tips in mechanosensory organs, bristles with open tips in chemosensory ones, or dome-shaped structures in campaniform sensilla.
A sensillum with a long, unicellular, setiform outgrowth that is strongly chitinized.

definition.value: This term is sometimes used to refer to the 'bristle-like' outgrowth only, but is here used to refer to the entire sensillum of which it is a part.

value.value: Any bristle that is innervated by a gustatory receptor neuron. It has pores to allow food stimuli to reach the neuron.
A long, unicellular, setiform outgrowth that is strongly chitinized and may be in connection with a sensory nerve.

A specialized, enlarged trichome-like structures that is located close to the base of a bristle. Bracts are induced by bristles, but are not a product of the bristle lineage (del Alamo et al., 2002 and refs therein). They are located on the proximal side of the bristle and share the same polarity. Bracts are found in the legs and wings.
Bristle that is innervated by a mechanosensory neuron that detects its movement due to wind, contact or other stimuli.
A sensillum of the adult whose external sensory structure is a hair or short thin bristle.

definition.value: Note that entomologists working in other species may call such sensilla trichoid, but Drosophila biologists typically reserve this for only the very smallest hairs. The reference for the term microchaeta among Drosophilist dates back to at least Lees and Waddington (1942).

value.value: An eo-type sensillum in which the cuticular part typically has the form of a papilla, bell or hollow cone receiving the distal process of a sensory neuron.
A sensillum of which the external part is a seta.

definition.value: Note that there is some variation in usage of this term throughout entomology, with some sources using it to refer to any sensillum with a hair or bristle cuticular specialization (e.g. see Chapman, 1998 FBrf0239230). Among the Dmel model organism community it is only used for the smallest of hairs/bristle, with sensilla with larger, thicker cuticular specializations being referred to as chaetae. We follow this usage. It should be noted, however, that there is no clear dividing line between macrochaeta and microchaeta or between microchaeta and trichoid sensillum.

value.value: A eo-type sensillum in which the external part has the form of a minute projecting cone or peg.

label.value: receptor lymph space of small basiconic sensillum

value.value: Any sensillar lymph space (FBbt:00007347) that is part of some small basiconic sensillum of antennal segment 3 (FBbt:00004176).

label.value: receptor lymph space of large basiconic sensillum

value.value: Any sensillar lymph space (FBbt:00007347) that is part of some large basiconic sensillum of antennal segment 3 (FBbt:00004175).

A general name for various olfactory or gustatory sense organs of conical shape in which the external process is sunken in a cavity of the body wall. Usually found in the extra-oral cavity or other mouthparts.
Sensillum that resembles a pit, with a terminal pore which is plugged by an electron-dense material. It can be innervated by one or several dendrites.
Sensillum that resembles a knob. Two of these sensilla are found in the terminal organ of the embryo/larva.
Sensillum that resembles a spot. One of these sensilla is found in the terminal organ of the embryo/larva.
